148–Overleden","1165–Male":"1165–Overleden","1168–Male":"1168–Overleden","1170–1233":"1170–1233","1146–Male":"1146–Overleden","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1148":"1148","1224":"1224","1146":"1146","1168":"1168","1233":"1233","circa 1170":"circa 1170","1165":"1165","1170":"1170","circa 1146":"circa 1146","circa 1168":"circa 1168","Rycote, Oxfordshire, England":"Rycote, Oxfordshire, England"},"en":{"circa 1146–":"about 1146–Deceased","1148–Female":"1148–Deceased","1165–Male":"1165–Deceased","1168–Male":"1168–Deceased","1170–1233":"1170–1233","1146–Male":"1146–Deceased","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1148":"1148","1224":"1224","1146":"1146","1168":"1168","1233":"1233","circa 1170":"about 1170","1165":"1165","1170":"1170","circa 1146":"about 1146","circa 1168":"about 1168","Rycote, Oxfordshire, England":"Rycote, Oxfordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":69,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":78,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":113,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Richard de Rycote was born about 1146, in Rycote, Oxfordshire, England. He married Mrs. de Rycote, given and maiden names unknown about 1168, in Rycote, Oxfordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"circa 1146–":"umbes 1146–Surnud","1148–Female":"1148–Surnud","1165–Male":"1165–Surnud","1168–Male":"1168–Surnud","1170–1233":"1170–1233","1146–Male":"1146–Surnud","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1148":"1148","1224":"1224","1146":"1146","1168":"1168","1233":"1233","circa 1170":"umbes 1170","1165":"1165","1170":"1170","circa 1146":"umbes 1146","circa 1168":"umbes 1168","Rycote, Oxfordshire, England":"Rycote, Oxfordshire, England"},"fi":{"circa 1146–":"noin 1146–Kuollut","1148–Female":"1148–Kuollut","1165–Male":"1165–Kuollut","1168–Male":"1168–Kuollut","1170–1233":"1170–1233","1146–Male":"1146–Kuollut","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1148":"1148","1224":"1224","1146":"1146","1168":"1168","1233":"1233","circa 1170":"noin 1170","1165":"1165","1170":"1170","circa 1146":"noin 1146","circa 1168":"noin 1168","Rycote, Oxfordshire, England":"Rycote, Oxfordshire, England"},"fr":{"circa 1146–":"environ 1146–Décédé","1148–Female":"1148–Décédée","1165–Male":"1165–Décédé","1168–Male":"1168–Décédé","1170–1233":"1170–1233","1146–Male":"1146–Décédé","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1148":"1148","1224":"1224","1146":"1146","1168":"1168","1233":"1233","circa 1170":"environ 1170","1165":"1165","1170":"1170","circa 1146":"environ 1146","circa 1168":"environ 1168","Rycote, Oxfordshire, England":"Rycote, Oxfordshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Richard de Rycote est né environ 1146, à Rycote, Oxfordshire, Angleterre. Il a épousé Mrs. de Rycote, given and maiden names unknown environ